A custom operator is just a function returning `OperatorFunction<T, R>`. Compose existing operators with the standalone `pipe` helper so it works with any source.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { tap } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function withLogging<T>(label: string): OperatorFunction<T, T> {
  return pipe(
    tap<T>({
      next: (v) => console.log(`[${label}] next`, v),
      error: (e) => console.error(`[${label}] error`, e),
      complete: () => console.log(`[${label}] complete`),
    })
  );
}

declare const source$: Observable<number>;
export const logged$: Observable<number> = source$.pipe(withLogging('tick'));
```

Because the return type is `OperatorFunction<T, T>`, the element type is preserved downstream in the pipe chain without any explicit annotation.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { map } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Tagged<T> {
  tag: string;
  value: T;
}

export function tagValues<T>(tag: string): OperatorFunction<T, Tagged<T>> {
  return pipe(
    map((value: T): Tagged<T> => ({ tag, value }))
  );
}

declare const numbers$: Observable<number>;
export const tagged$: Observable<Tagged<number>> = numbers$.pipe(tagValues('metric'));
```

`OperatorFunction<T, Tagged<T>>` changes the output type — TypeScript threads `Tagged<number>` through `numbers$.pipe(tagValues(...))` automatically.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { filter } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function filterByKey<T, K extends keyof T>(
  key: K,
  value: T[K]
): OperatorFunction<T, T> {
  return pipe(
    filter((item: T): boolean => item[key] === value)
  );
}

interface Order {
  id: string;
  status: 'open' | 'closed';
}

declare const orders$: Observable<Order>;
export const openOrders$: Observable<Order> = orders$.pipe(filterByKey('status', 'open'));
```

The `K extends keyof T` constraint keeps the key checked at compile time and forces `value` to match `T[K]` — mistyped field names are caught by `tsc --strict`.

A custom operator is a function whose return type is `OperatorFunction<T, R>` — literally `(source: Observable<T>) => Observable<R>`. You compose it from existing operators via the standalone `pipe` from `'rxjs'` (not the `.pipe` method on observables, which is instance-scoped).

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { map, scan } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Timed<T> {
  value: T;
  deltaMs: number;
}

export function elapsed<T>(): OperatorFunction<T, Timed<T>> {
  return pipe(
    map((value: T): { value: T; t: number } => ({ value, t: Date.now() })),
    scan(
      (acc, curr) => ({ value: curr.value, deltaMs: curr.t - acc.t, t: curr.t }),
      { value: undefined as unknown as T, deltaMs: 0, t: Date.now() }
    ),
    map(({ value, deltaMs }): Timed<T> => ({ value, deltaMs }))
  );
}

declare const ticks$: Observable<string>;
export const timed$: Observable<Timed<string>> = ticks$.pipe(elapsed());
```

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { tap } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function throttleLog<T>(every: number, label: string): OperatorFunction<T, T> {
  let count = 0;
  return pipe(
    tap<T>((value: T) => {
      count += 1;
      if (count % every === 0) {
        console.log(`[${label}] #${count}`, value);
      }
    })
  );
}

declare const events$: Observable<string>;
export const sampled$: Observable<string> = events$.pipe(throttleLog(10, 'events'));
```

Note: the `count` closure is shared across subscribers. If you need per-subscriber state, wrap the body in `new Observable` and allocate there.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction } from 'rxjs';
import { defaultIfEmpty } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function withDefault<T>(fallback: T): OperatorFunction<T, T> {
  return (source: Observable<T>): Observable<T> =>
    source.pipe(defaultIfEmpty<T, T>(fallback));
}

declare const maybeEmpty$: Observable<number>;
export const safe$: Observable<number> = maybeEmpty$.pipe(withDefault(0));
```

Writing the operator as an arrow `(source) => source.pipe(...)` is equivalent to composing via the standalone `pipe` — pick whichever reads best for your team.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { distinctUntilChanged, filter, map } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function cleanStrings(): OperatorFunction<string, string> {
  return pipe(
    map((s: string): string => s.trim()),
    filter((s: string): boolean => s.length > 0),
    distinctUntilChanged()
  );
}

declare const input$: Observable<string>;
export const terms$: Observable<string> = input$.pipe(cleanStrings());
```

The factory form (a function returning `OperatorFunction<…>`) lets you parameterise later without breaking existing call sites.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { bufferCount, filter } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function bufferByCount<T>(size: number): OperatorFunction<T, T[]> {
  return pipe(
    bufferCount<T>(size),
    filter((buf: T[]): boolean => buf.length === size)
  );
}

declare const stream$: Observable<number>;
export const chunks$: Observable<number[]> = stream$.pipe(bufferByCount(5));
```

The trailing `filter` drops the final short buffer produced when the source completes mid-window — handy when you only want full chunks.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe, throwError } from 'rxjs';
import { mergeMap, of } from 'rxjs';

interface Authed<T> {
  token: string;
  payload: T;
}

export class MissingTokenError extends Error {
  constructor() {
    super('missing auth token');
    this.name = 'MissingTokenError';
  }
}

export function requireAuth<T>(): OperatorFunction<Authed<T>, T> {
  return pipe(
    mergeMap((env: Authed<T>): Observable<T> =>
      env.token.length > 0 ? of(env.payload) : throwError((): Error => new MissingTokenError())
    )
  );
}

declare const envelope$: Observable<Authed<string>>;
export const body$: Observable<string> = envelope$.pipe(requireAuth());
```

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { throttleTime } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function rateLimit<T>(ms: number): OperatorFunction<T, T> {
  return pipe(
    throttleTime<T>(ms, undefined, { leading: true, trailing: false })
  );
}

declare const click$: Observable<MouseEvent>;
export const limitedClicks$: Observable<MouseEvent> = click$.pipe(rateLimit(500));
```

`{ leading: true, trailing: false }` emits the first event immediately and drops subsequent events inside the window — matches most UI throttle expectations.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { map } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function mapToShape<T, R>(project: (value: T) => R): OperatorFunction<T, R> {
  return pipe(
    map((value: T): R => project(value))
  );
}

interface User { id: string; name: string; }
interface UserLabel { label: string; }

declare const users$: Observable<User>;
export const labels$: Observable<UserLabel> = users$.pipe(
  mapToShape((u: User): UserLabel => ({ label: `${u.name} (${u.id})` }))
);
```

It is effectively a typed alias for `map` — the value is in naming intent at call sites and the ability to attach documentation to a project-specific operator.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { filter } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function onlyDefined<T>(): OperatorFunction<T | undefined, T> {
  return pipe(
    filter((value: T | undefined): value is T => value !== undefined)
  );
}

declare const maybe$: Observable<string | undefined>;
export const defined$: Observable<string> = maybe$.pipe(onlyDefined<string>());
```

The type predicate `value is T` is what removes `undefined` from the downstream type — `tsc --strict` now sees `Observable<string>` after the operator.

You build it the same way as any custom operator — the `BehaviorSubject` lives outside and the operator consumes/combines it. The operator signature stays `OperatorFunction<T, R>`.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable, OperatorFunction, combineLatest, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { map } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Toggles { debug: boolean; }

export function attachFlags<T>(
  flags$: BehaviorSubject<Toggles>
): OperatorFunction<T, { value: T; debug: boolean }> {
  return (source: Observable<T>) =>
    combineLatest([source, flags$]).pipe(
      map(([value, flags]: [T, Toggles]) => ({ value, debug: flags.debug }))
    );
}

declare const events$: Observable<string>;
const flags$ = new BehaviorSubject<Toggles>({ debug: false });
export const enriched$ = events$.pipe(attachFlags(flags$));
```

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, timer } from 'rxjs';
import { retry } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function retryWithBackoff<T>(maxAttempts: number, baseMs: number): OperatorFunction<T, T> {
  return (source: Observable<T>): Observable<T> =>
    source.pipe(
      retry<T>({
        count: maxAttempts,
        delay: (_error: unknown, attempt: number): Observable<number> =>
          timer(baseMs * 2 ** (attempt - 1))
      })
    );
}

declare const fetch$: Observable<string>;
export const resilient$: Observable<string> = fetch$.pipe(retryWithBackoff(3, 200));
```

The factory form keeps the retry policy co-located and reusable — every HTTP stream in the app can import this one operator.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { map } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function keyed<T, K extends keyof T>(key: K): OperatorFunction<T, T[K]> {
  return pipe(
    map((item: T): T[K] => item[key])
  );
}

interface User { id: string; email: string; }

declare const users$: Observable<User>;
export const emails$: Observable<string> = users$.pipe(keyed('email'));
```

`K extends keyof T` makes the key safe at compile time; `T[K]` threads the field's actual type into the downstream `Observable`.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { defaultIfEmpty, take } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function firstOrDefault<T>(fallback: T): OperatorFunction<T, T> {
  return pipe(
    take<T>(1),
    defaultIfEmpty<T, T>(fallback)
  );
}

declare const probe$: Observable<number>;
export const sample$: Observable<number> = probe$.pipe(firstOrDefault(-1));
```

`take(1)` completes after the first value; `defaultIfEmpty` kicks in when the source completes without emitting — the two together make a safe "read once" primitive.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { map } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface WithCorrelation<T> {
  correlationId: string;
  payload: T;
}

export function withCorrelation<T>(
  makeId: () => string
): OperatorFunction<T, WithCorrelation<T>> {
  return pipe(
    map((payload: T): WithCorrelation<T> => ({ correlationId: makeId(), payload }))
  );
}

declare const requests$: Observable<string>;
export const traced$: Observable<WithCorrelation<string>> = requests$.pipe(
  withCorrelation((): string => Math.random().toString(36).slice(2))
);
```

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { map } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function ensureArray<T>(): OperatorFunction<T | T[], T[]> {
  return pipe(
    map((value: T | T[]): T[] => (Array.isArray(value) ? value : [value]))
  );
}

declare const payload$: Observable<string | string[]>;
export const items$: Observable<string[]> = payload$.pipe(ensureArray<string>());
```

Note: explicit `<string>` on the call site disambiguates the generic when the source type is a union — TypeScript otherwise has trouble inferring `T` from `T | T[]`.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { debounceTime, distinctUntilChanged, filter, map } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function sanitiseInput(
  debounceMs: number = 300,
  minLength: number = 2
): OperatorFunction<string, string> {
  return pipe(
    debounceTime(debounceMs),
    map((s: string): string => s.trim()),
    filter((s: string): boolean => s.length >= minLength),
    distinctUntilChanged()
  );
}

declare const keystroke$: Observable<string>;
export const query$: Observable<string> = keystroke$.pipe(sanitiseInput(300, 2));
```

Naming the operator expresses the intent ("this is a search input sanitiser") better than an inline four-operator block repeated across components.

```ts
import { Observable, OperatorFunction, pipe } from 'rxjs';
import { filter, pairwise } from 'rxjs/operators';

export function pairWithPrevious<T>(): OperatorFunction<T, [T, T]> {
  return pipe(
    pairwise<T>(),
    filter((pair: [T, T]): pair is [T, T] => pair.length === 2)
  );
}

declare const ticks$: Observable<number>;
export const pairs$: Observable<[number, number]> = ticks$.pipe(pairWithPrevious());
```

`pairwise` already types its output as `[T, T]` — the explicit generic on the factory makes the intent and downstream type obvious to readers.

Apply `shareReplay({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })` once on the cold source. Every new subscriber replays the cached value; the upstream subscription is released when the last subscriber unsubscribes.

```ts
import { Observable, defer, of } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Config {
  apiUrl: string;
  flagA: boolean;
}

declare function fetchConfig(): Promise<Config>;

export const config$: Observable<Config> = defer((): Promise<Config> => fetchConfig()).pipe(
  shareReplay<Config>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

// Two subscribers share a single fetchConfig() call.
config$.subscribe((c: Config): void => console.log('A', c.apiUrl));
config$.subscribe((c: Config): void => console.log('B', c.apiUrl));
```

`refCount: true` is the key — when the subscriber count drops to zero, the upstream unsubscribes and the cached value is dropped, so the next subscriber re-runs the fetch.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface UserProfile {
  id: string;
  displayName: string;
  avatarUrl: string;
}

declare function fetchProfile(id: string): Promise<UserProfile>;

export function makeProfile$(id: string): Observable<UserProfile> {
  return defer((): Promise<UserProfile> => fetchProfile(id)).pipe(
    shareReplay<UserProfile>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
  );
}

const alice$ = makeProfile$('alice');
alice$.subscribe((p: UserProfile): void => console.log('nav', p.displayName));
alice$.subscribe((p: UserProfile): void => console.log('footer', p.displayName));
```

One `fetchProfile('alice')` call, two subscribers. `defer` matters here — without it the promise would start immediately when `makeProfile$` is called.

`shareReplay` multicasts a cold source and replays the last N values to late subscribers. The v7+ object form accepts `{ bufferSize, refCount }`. With `refCount: true`, when the subscriber count drops to zero the operator unsubscribes from the source and discards the buffer — the next subscriber re-runs the source. With `refCount: false` (the default) the source stays subscribed forever, which can leak.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Settings {
  theme: 'light' | 'dark';
  locale: string;
}

declare function loadSettings(): Promise<Settings>;

export const settings$: Observable<Settings> = defer(
  (): Promise<Settings> => loadSettings()
).pipe(
  shareReplay<Settings>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

settings$.subscribe((s: Settings): void => console.log('header', s.theme));
settings$.subscribe((s: Settings): void => console.log('body', s.locale));
```

Use the single operator `shareReplay({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })`. The old `publishReplay(1).refCount()` pairing was replaced by this config-object form in rxjs v7.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Token { jwt: string; expiresAt: number; }

declare function fetchToken(): Promise<Token>;

export const token$: Observable<Token> = defer((): Promise<Token> => fetchToken()).pipe(
  shareReplay<Token>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);
```

Without `refCount: true` the upstream stays subscribed forever — fine for a process-wide singleton, a leak for anything scoped to a component lifecycle.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Product { id: string; name: string; priceCents: number; }

declare function fetchProducts(): Promise<Product[]>;

export const products$: Observable<Product[]> = defer(
  (): Promise<Product[]> => fetchProducts()
).pipe(
  shareReplay<Product[]>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

products$.subscribe((ps: Product[]): void => console.log('grid', ps.length));
products$.subscribe((ps: Product[]): void => console.log('sidebar', ps.length));
```

The second subscriber gets the cached array immediately — `fetchProducts()` only runs once so long as there is at least one subscriber.

Pass `{ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true }` — the `refCount: true` flag is exactly the "release when subscriber count hits zero" behaviour.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Config { endpoint: string; timeoutMs: number; }

declare function loadConfig(): Promise<Config>;

export const config$: Observable<Config> = defer(
  (): Promise<Config> => loadConfig()
).pipe(
  shareReplay<Config>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);
```

Picking `refCount: false` (the default) keeps the upstream alive forever — that is only what you want for a genuinely process-lifetime singleton.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface FeatureFlags {
  newCheckout: boolean;
  darkMode: boolean;
}

declare function fetchFlags(): Promise<FeatureFlags>;

export const flags$: Observable<FeatureFlags> = defer(
  (): Promise<FeatureFlags> => fetchFlags()
).pipe(
  shareReplay<FeatureFlags>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

flags$.subscribe((f: FeatureFlags): void => console.log('checkout', f.newCheckout));
flags$.subscribe((f: FeatureFlags): void => console.log('nav', f.darkMode));
```

The two components share one HTTP call. When both unmount and unsubscribe, `refCount: true` tears the upstream down; the next mount will re-fetch, picking up any flag changes.

```ts
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { fromFetch } from 'rxjs/fetch';
import { shareReplay, switchMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Repo { id: number; fullName: string; }

export const repo$: Observable<Repo> = fromFetch('/api/repo').pipe(
  switchMap((res: Response): Promise<Repo> => res.json() as Promise<Repo>),
  shareReplay<Repo>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

repo$.subscribe((r: Repo): void => console.log('header', r.fullName));
repo$.subscribe((r: Repo): void => console.log('detail', r.fullName));
```

Both subscribers share one HTTP round trip. `refCount: true` avoids leaking the underlying fetch subscription once everyone unsubscribes.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

function expensive(): number {
  let total = 0;
  for (let i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i += 1) total += i;
  return total;
}

export const result$: Observable<number> = defer(
  (): Observable<number> => new Observable<number>((sub) => { sub.next(expensive()); sub.complete(); })
).pipe(
  shareReplay<number>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

result$.subscribe((n: number): void => console.log('a', n));
result$.subscribe((n: number): void => console.log('b', n));
result$.subscribe((n: number): void => console.log('c', n));
```

`expensive()` runs exactly once; the later subscribers replay the cached value.

`refCount: true` tracks active subscribers and unsubscribes from the upstream when the count drops to zero — next subscriber re-runs the source. `refCount: false` keeps the upstream subscribed forever even with zero subscribers, which is a memory leak unless the source is an intentionally process-wide singleton.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Session { userId: string; expiresAt: number; }

declare function loadSession(): Promise<Session>;

export const session$: Observable<Session> = defer(
  (): Promise<Session> => loadSession()
).pipe(
  shareReplay<Session>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

session$.subscribe((s: Session): void => console.log('guard', s.userId));
session$.subscribe((s: Session): void => console.log('profile', s.userId));
```

The v7 replacement is a single `shareReplay` call with the config-object form:

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Inventory { sku: string; count: number; }

declare function loadInventory(): Promise<Inventory>;

export const inventory$: Observable<Inventory> = defer(
  (): Promise<Inventory> => loadInventory()
).pipe(
  shareReplay<Inventory>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);
```

The old `publishReplay(1), refCount()` pair became redundant once `shareReplay` got a proper config object — one operator does the work.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Rates { base: string; quotes: Record<string, number>; }

declare function fetchRates(): Promise<Rates>;

export const rates$: Observable<Rates> = defer(
  (): Promise<Rates> => fetchRates()
).pipe(
  shareReplay<Rates>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

const sub1 = rates$.subscribe((r: Rates): void => console.log('a', r.base));
const sub2 = rates$.subscribe((r: Rates): void => console.log('b', r.base));
sub1.unsubscribe();
sub2.unsubscribe();
// Next subscriber triggers a fresh fetchRates() because refCount hit zero.
rates$.subscribe((r: Rates): void => console.log('fresh', r.base));
```

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Notification { id: string; kind: 'info' | 'error'; message: string; }

declare function fetchNotifications(): Promise<Notification[]>;

export const notifications$: Observable<Notification[]> = defer(
  (): Promise<Notification[]> => fetchNotifications()
).pipe(
  shareReplay<Notification[]>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

notifications$.subscribe((ns: Notification[]): void => console.log('bell', ns.length));
notifications$.subscribe((ns: Notification[]): void => console.log('dropdown', ns.length));
```

One fetch backs the bell icon and the dropdown. The explicit `<Notification[]>` generic on `shareReplay` documents the cached shape for readers.

```ts
import { Observable, interval } from 'rxjs';
import { map, shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface SensorReading { tempC: number; ts: number; }

export const sensor$: Observable<SensorReading> = interval(1000).pipe(
  map((i: number): SensorReading => ({ tempC: 20 + Math.sin(i) * 5, ts: Date.now() })),
  shareReplay<SensorReading>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

sensor$.subscribe((r: SensorReading): void => console.log('widget-a', r.tempC));
sensor$.subscribe((r: SensorReading): void => console.log('widget-b', r.tempC));
```

Both widgets see the same emissions in lockstep — without `shareReplay`, each subscriber would start its own `interval`, drifting out of sync.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface AuthCheck { userId: string; roles: string[]; }

declare function checkAuth(): Promise<AuthCheck>;

export const auth$: Observable<AuthCheck> = defer(
  (): Promise<AuthCheck> => checkAuth()
).pipe(
  shareReplay<AuthCheck>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

auth$.subscribe((a: AuthCheck): void => console.log('route-guard', a.userId));
auth$.subscribe((a: AuthCheck): void => console.log('nav-menu', a.roles.length));
```

One `checkAuth()` call feeds both the route guard and the nav menu. When both unsubscribe, `refCount: true` releases the upstream so the next check is a fresh call.

Pass `bufferSize: 5` in the config object. Late subscribers receive the last 5 buffered values on subscription.

```ts
import { Observable, Subject } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface LogLine { level: 'info' | 'warn' | 'error'; message: string; }

const source$ = new Subject<LogLine>();

export const recent$: Observable<LogLine> = source$.pipe(
  shareReplay<LogLine>({ bufferSize: 5, refCount: true })
);

source$.next({ level: 'info', message: 'a' });
source$.next({ level: 'info', message: 'b' });
source$.next({ level: 'warn', message: 'c' });
// Late subscriber gets the buffered 3 entries plus any subsequent emissions.
recent$.subscribe((l: LogLine): void => console.log(l.level, l.message));
```

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { finalize, shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

let fetches = 0;

export const counted$: Observable<number> = defer((): Observable<number> => {
  fetches += 1;
  return new Observable<number>((sub) => { sub.next(fetches); sub.complete(); });
}).pipe(
  finalize((): void => console.log('upstream released')),
  shareReplay<number>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

const a = counted$.subscribe((n: number): void => console.log('a', n));
const b = counted$.subscribe((n: number): void => console.log('b', n));
a.unsubscribe();
b.unsubscribe();
// 'upstream released' prints here — refCount hit zero.
counted$.subscribe((n: number): void => console.log('c', n));
// Fresh fetch: fetches increments.
```

Define the observable once at module scope with `shareReplay({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })` and import it into both components.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Dashboard { revenueCents: number; orders: number; }

declare function fetchDashboard(): Promise<Dashboard>;

export const dashboard$: Observable<Dashboard> = defer(
  (): Promise<Dashboard> => fetchDashboard()
).pipe(
  shareReplay<Dashboard>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);
```

Component A and component B both subscribe; they share one call. When both unmount, `refCount: true` tears the upstream down so remounting re-fetches with fresh data.

```ts
import { Observable, Subject } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface WsEvent { kind: 'open' | 'message' | 'close'; payload?: string; }

const raw$ = new Subject<WsEvent>();

export const ws$: Observable<WsEvent> = raw$.pipe(
  shareReplay<WsEvent>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
);

ws$.subscribe((e: WsEvent): void => console.log('panel-a', e.kind));
ws$.subscribe((e: WsEvent): void => console.log('panel-b', e.kind));

raw$.next({ kind: 'open' });
raw$.next({ kind: 'message', payload: 'hi' });
```

Late subscribers get the most recent event immediately; live subscribers see new events as they arrive. Both behaviours fall out of `bufferSize: 1`.

```ts
import { Observable, defer } from 'rxjs';
import { shareReplay } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface FeatureResult {
  id: string;
  label: string;
  enabled: boolean;
}

declare function fetchFeature(id: string): Promise<FeatureResult>;

export function makeFeature$(id: string): Observable<FeatureResult> {
  return defer((): Promise<FeatureResult> => fetchFeature(id)).pipe(
    shareReplay<FeatureResult>({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true })
  );
}

const checkout$ = makeFeature$('checkout-v2');
checkout$.subscribe((f: FeatureResult): void => console.log('page', f.enabled));
checkout$.subscribe((f: FeatureResult): void => console.log('nav', f.enabled));
```

One `fetchFeature('checkout-v2')` call serves both subscribers. `refCount: true` guarantees the upstream is released when both unsubscribe — the next subscriber would re-fetch cleanly.
